[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426484&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426484&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

It is all well and good to have cut-overs, but lets not forget about
old mail in our files that may deserve a reply, sometime after the
cutover date.  I sure hope that our tables can keep old addresses like
host.ARPA around as nicknames until we have drained our intrerest in
processing mail in our decreasingly active old mail files.

I find it perplexing (and vexing from time to time) to see the problem
of processing old mail ignored so much of the time.  The complete model
for mail UA Interworking (RFCs 733, 822, X.400) must include reasonable
interoperability between my UA of 1975 and my UA of 1989.  I may not
want to answer any of those items, but I do want to be able to search
and sort and select on my collection of old mail.  (I call it research.)

Of course, we cannot expect all addresses and host names circa 1975 to
be operable or replyable in 1989, but lets not plan to cutover with
Sept 14, 1985 addresses not being repliable on Sept 15, 1985.  We must
have a long overlap of some kind.

Cheers - Stef

